charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story:
I'm collecting vital funds for the British Heart Foundation, to power pioneering research into heart and cardiovascular diseases. The money we raise will help beat heartbreak forever.

Heart disease is such a common and devastating factor in our lives, I thought to myself, "If I want to be around for a long time, to watch my children grow up, have their own children, and hopefully see them have children, I either would have had to have children at the age of 20 (about 10 years late for that one), or I need to start taking care of myself now. I have chosen to build up my very important heart muscle, learn to take a moment for myself, and be completely able to run away from zombies in the apocalypse. Very important.

charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story:
The pandemic is the biggest challenge we've faced in our 60 year history. And it's led to us being forced to make the devastating decision to cut our 2020 research budget in half. So the truth is, we've never needed people like you more. 

Virtual fundraising challenges like Dechox are a way to help us keep up the pace of progress. Your willpower will be funnelled into ground-breaking science and support for the people who need us most.

Because despite everything else happening at the moment, heart and circulatory diseases are still the world's biggest killers. For the sake of our mums and dads, brothers and sisters, grandparents and friends - we can't drop the ball now.

charity.description: With your support, we aim to fund over Â£100 million of research each year into all heart and circulatory diseases and the things that cause them. Heart diseases. Stroke. Vascular dementia. Diabetes. They're all connected, and they're all under our microscope. Together we can beat heartbreak forever.
charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story:
The pandemic is the biggest challenge we've faced in our 60 year history. And it's led to us being forced to make the devastating decision to cut our 2020 research budget in half. So the truth is, we've never needed people like you more. 

Virtual fundraising challenges like Dechox are a way to help us keep up the pace of progress. Your willpower will be funnelled into ground-breaking science and support for the people who need us most.

Because despite everything else happening at the moment, heart and circulatory diseases are still the world's biggest killers. For the sake of our mums and dads, brothers and sisters, grandparents and friends - we can't drop the ball now.

charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story: Thanks for visiting my page. I'm raising money for the British Heart Foundation and I'd be so grateful for your support. The BHF has helped halve the number of people dying from heart and circulatory disease in the UK but sadly every day hundreds of people lose their lives. It's only thanks to support from people like us that the BHF can create new treatments and discover new cures. Â£24 could pay for two hours of research by an early career scientist, but every pound helps so please give what you can to help me hit my target. Thanks!

charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story:
This cause is very close to my heart (sorry for the pun!) I want to raise as much money as I can for this great charity. This last year the British Heart Foundation have become very important and vital to my family. Before this I wasnâ€™t aware of the shocking number of people it affects, they are vital to the fight against heart disease. They help so many people and I want to do what I can to support them and to give something back.Â 

The pandemic is the biggest challenge we've faced in our 60 year history. And it's led to us being forced to make the devastating decision to cut our 2020 research budget in half. So the truth is, we've never needed people like you more. Virtual fundraising challenges like Dechox are a way to help us keep up the pace of progress. Your willpower will be funnelled into ground-breaking science and support for the people who need us most.Because despite everything else happening at the moment, heart and circulatory diseases are still the world's biggest killers.Â 

For the sake of our mums and dads, brothers and sisters, grandparents and friends - we can't drop the ball now.

eventName: Run 100 Miles in March for Math
story: My older Brother Matthew has recently died very suddenly following a heart attack, just a month after his 40th birthday. This came as a complete shock to myself, my family and Matthews wife, and has left us all totally shocked and devastated. In his memory and to raise money for the British Heart foundation, myself and my husband will be looking for sponsorship to run 100 miles throughout March. Any donations are greatly appreciated and will be donated to the British Heart Foundation. Thank you all.
title: Hannah 's Run 100 Miles in March for Math
rememberedPersonSummary.name: Matthew  Willcox

story: Thanks for visiting my page. I'm raising money for the British Heart Foundation and I'd be so grateful for your support. The BHF has helped halve the number of people dying from heart and circulatory disease in the UK but sadly every day hundreds of people lose their lives. It's only thanks to support from people like us that the BHF can create new treatments and discover new cures. Â£24 could pay for two hours of research by an early career scientist, but every pound helps so please give what you can to help me hit my target. Thanks!

story:
March is going to be hell on earth 🌎

No chocolate 🍫 no sweets 🍬 or soda.

For anyone that knows me and how much I live for chocolate, you will know how difficult this is going to be for me.

Why would I make myself suffer this?


So many of my family have had help to keep them alive because their heart â¤ï¸ as it is not as healthy as it should be.

It is Valentine's Day, and this is how I am showing them I love 😍


So would you like a daily basis video diary to make sure I haven't killed anyone? 😂😂😂


Share this if you can x

So the truth is, we've never needed people like you more. Virtual fundraising challenges like Dechox are a way to help us keep up the pace of progress. story:
In May 2001, 20 years ago this year I lost my Dad, my best friend, the hero who kept me safe to a fatal heart attack. Everyone who knew him had nothing but kind things to say about him. He was everyoneâ€™s friend and looked out for so many people. Last week we found out he had 2 heart attacks before this one took him, and we have been filled with what ifs since. Itâ€™s broke us all over again.

Everyone who knows me knows I love chocolate, sweets and Pepsi max, so giving up all 3 is going to be a challenge. I know it wonâ€™t bring my Dad back but it might help prevent someone else going through the pain I have.

You donâ€™t have to donate much just every little helps.

charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story:
To mark the 10th memorial anniversary of losing Joe to a massive heart attack at a young age, we are challenging ourselves to change a habit that will help improve our hearts and therefore reduce the risk that this happens to others.

Joe passed away on 13th March 2011 and has been sorely missed by his partner Angela, his childrenÂ Laura, Graeme and Bethony, family and many friends.

This is a great opportunity for us to raise the awareness of heart disease, donate some vital funds towards the research to beat future heartbreak and do something different to reduce our risk of this.

So in memory of Joe, we're collecting vital funds for the British Heart Foundation, to power pioneering research into heart and cardiovascular diseases. The money we raise will help beat heartbreak forever.

charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story:
Thanks for visiting our page. We are raising money for the British Heart Foundation and would be so grateful for your support.Â Â 

In September 2018, I contracted Infective Endocarditis (staphylococcus aureus) and was taken into Darent Valley Hospital for one week. I was then allowed back home to receive treatment there, but two days later my heart rate severely dropped and I was taken into Critical Care at St Thomasâ€™ Hospital.Â 

A transoesophageal echocardiogram (a camera down my throat) revealed an undiagnosed Bicuspid Aortic Valve (BAV) which is regurgitating my blood backwards into my left ventricle. The endocarditis also attacked my sinoatrial node (the heartâ€™s natural pacemaker). I quickly had a temporary pacemaker fitted (whilst fully awake) which sat on the outside of my skin and connected through a vein in my neck before I had a permanent pacemaker implanted. I will need surgery in the future to replace my valve.Â 

I was in St Thomas for 5 weeks and Rebecca and I are incredibly grateful for the exceptional care and medical attention I received then and continue to receive now, all of which is underpinned by research from the British Heart Foundation. The information and resources from the BHF provided clarity and a sense of support in what was a challenging time.

The British Heart Foundation needs our support more than ever. Covid-19 has devastated the BHFâ€™s income and therefore their investment in life saving research.Â

eventName: Shaving my head for cancer research UK
story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.

So my story isn't really mine to tell, it's my brave wonderful Dad's, but as he is sadly not here to tell it, I will...Â 

My Dad was diagnosed with non-hodgekins lymphoma in 2016 and underwent all treatments but sadly it had spread to his brain from the spine and in June 2017 we said goodbye to him. He was my hero and nothing made me prouder than the staggering amount of money he raised in his last few weeks with us. Dad raised over Â£6000 to help others in their fights against cancer!Â 

I wanted to do something in his honour to raise some more money towards a charity most of us will have come into contact with at some point or another in our lives, directly or indirectly!Â 

During these odd times it's tricky as to what we can do to raise money, but I can shave my head, even though the thought of it scares me and makes me feel so vulnberable, it's not half as scary, or won't take nearly as much bravery as what people fighting cancer have to face.

Please get behind me, donate what you can and share my dad's story on social media with the link to my fundraising page!Â 

With love from Rachel Speck xx

charity.description: Marie Curie provides care and support for people living with any terminal illness across the UK. Our nurses work night and day in peopleâ€™s homes and our hospices offer specialist care. We also support people emotionally, provide practical information, and match them with trained volunteers.
charity.name: Marie Curie
story:
This March, Morrisons and Marie Curie are working side by side to raise vital funds for frontline nurses to help dying people and their loved ones.

This has been a hard year for everyone. Weve faced challenging times as a nation, and we know it's the small moments that bring people together. Such moments can be made possible for dying people and their loved ones by the expert care of Marie Curie Nurses, who can bring care, comfort and clarity at the very toughest time. 

Your support means the world to people affected by terminal illness.  From picking your daffodil in-store and wearing it with pride, to taking on your own fundraising challenge you're making vital care possible.

Put simply, without the support people like you highly skilled Marie Curie Nurses couldn't continue giving vital care to people living with a terminal illness and their families.
title: Karen's Marie curie

Name: Karen's Marie curie

charity.description: Marie Curie provides care and support for people living with any terminal illness across the UK. Our nurses work night and day in peopleâ€™s homes and our hospices offer specialist care. We also support people emotionally, provide practical information, and match them with trained volunteers.
charity.name: Marie Curie
story:
Every day of your life matters from the first to the last. We believe that everyone living with a terminal illness should be able to get the most from the time they have left, however hard that may sometimes feel. 
We'll be here for you and your family when you may feel like no-one else is, to help you cope when you don't know how. Marie Curie Nurses care for you in your home, when you need them most, day or night. Our hospices are at the heart of communities around the UK. And our trained volunteers and advisers are here for you with practical information and support when you don't know what to do next or just need to talk. 
We'll be by your side with care and support every step of the way, bringing light in the darkest hours.

charity.description: Marie Curie provides care and support for people living with any terminal illness across the UK. Our nurses work night and day in peopleâ€™s homes and our hospices offer specialist care. We also support people emotionally, provide practical information, and match them with trained volunteers.
charity.name: Marie Curie
story:
Every day of your life matters from the first to the last. We believe that everyone living with a terminal illness should be able to get the most from the time they have left, however hard that may sometimes feel. 
We'll be here for you and your family when you may feel like no-one else is, to help you cope when you don't know how. Marie Curie Nurses care for you in your home, when you need them most, day or night. Our hospices are at the heart of communities around the UK. And our trained volunteers and advisers are here for you with practical information and support when you don't know what to do next or just need to talk. 
We'll be by your side with care and support every step of the way, bringing light in the darkest hours.

charity.description: Marie Curie provides care and support for people living with any terminal illness across the UK. Our nurses work night and day in peopleâ€™s homes and our hospices offer specialist care. We also support people emotionally, provide practical information, and match them with trained volunteers.
charity.name: Marie Curie
story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.

I have decided to take part in Marie Curie Step into Spring as I have witnessed first hand the exceptional level of care and support that this charity provide.

I myself fought cancer last year in 2020 and feel that it is important to share my story.Â  Please do not ignore the signs from your own body as you know yourself better than anyone.Â  If telling my story can help just one person then it is 100% worth it.

As part of my journey and rehabilitation I have decided to take on this challenge.Â  While 10,000 step per day might not seem alot to some of my friends it will push me physically, give me a target and help me on my way to regaining my fitness while helping raise funds for Marie Curie.

Marie Curie provide end of life care for all terminal illnesses and any donations no matter how large or small will be greatly appreciated.

Thank you for reading my story.....time to get walking!

Love Sharon x

Every day of your life matters from the first to the last. We believe that everyone living with a terminal illness should be able to get the most from the time they have left, however hard that may sometimes feel. 
We'll be here for you and your family when you may feel like no-one else is, to help you cope when you don't know how. Marie Curie Nurses care for you in your home, when you need them most, day or night. Our hospices are at the heart of communities around the UK. And our trained volunteers and advisers are here for you with practical information and support when you don't know what to do next or just need to talk. 
We'll be by your side with care and support every step of the way, bringing light in the darkest hours.

charity.name: WWF-UK
story:
There is so many charities I want to support; Mental health charities, Medical research charities, Dogs Trust, RSPCA, Oxfam, LQBTQI + charities, and the list goes on..
In the end I decided that WWF was best suited as I believe it enables a better life for us all. Only in a world of balance can we thrive, with better chances of fighting mental health issues, physical illnesses and environmental challenges.
_____________________________________________________________________

Throughout my life my connection to nature has always helped me through difficult periods, and it still continues to do. It gives me a moment of peace to reflect and it puts things into perspective. I'm like most people, I probably could be a better eco warrior, I probably could do a lot more, but like most people I'm also just trying to be better every day.Â And that's what this challenge is about. Be a bit better every day.Â Walk the walk if you're going to talk the talk.Â 

So here I am. Taking on a challenge this summer of walking 100km around the Lake District with my boyfriend Simon who will be raising funds for Mental Health UK. I love walking/hiking, I love nature and I love my partner in crime. We are both just trying to keep moving forward in life, one step at a time. Hopefully we can also help others along the way, and hopefully you can find it in you to help us help others.

Thank you for visiting my Just Giving Page, that means a lot to me. If you choose to donate it would absolutely mean the world to me, and hopefully it means the world to you to. We're all in this together.

_____________________________________________________________________

WWF is at the heart of global efforts to address the worldâ€™s most important environmental challenges: safeguarding the natural world, tackling climate change and enabling people to use only their fair share of natural resources.
Together we can build a future where people and nature thrive.Â 
Find out more by visiting wwf.org.uk

charity.name: Oxfam
story:
We're walking 20,000km from St Albans (UK) to Cox's Bazar (Bangladesh), visiting Oxfam projects along the way. 

We'll see the challenges communities face from conflict, to Covid-19 to the impact of the climate emergency and how Oxfam is responding to support communities to thrive, not just survive. 

With your support, Oxfam can continue its life-saving work, it can continue to put together packages of food, give farming support, set up foodbanks, support education for women and girls, and provide cash to buy essentials.

For each Â£15 we raise, we could help more women to understand their rights, challenge discrimination and to take up leadership roles within their local communities.

For each Â£35, we could help families access emergency food supplies. 

Â£45 could provide one of our new handwashing stations to enable frequent handwashing and disease prevention.

With your support, communities can come together to help each other.

charity.description: Right now, millions of children are in danger. They face violence, disease, hunger and the chaos of war and disaster. Unicef ensures more children get life-saving food, vaccinations, education and protection than anyone else. With your help, we can build a safer world for children. unicef.org.uk
charity.name: Unicef UK
story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit our JustGiving page.

The Independent reports that 9 out of 10 people in 70 low-income countries are unlikely to be vaccinated against Covid-19 this year because the majority of the most promising vaccines coming on-stream have been bought up by the west, campaigners have said.

As theÂ first people get vaccinated in the UK, the Peopleâ€™s Vaccine Alliance have warned that the deals done by rich countriesâ€™ governments will leave the poor at the mercy of the rampaging virus. Rich countries with 14% of the worldâ€™s population have secured 53% of the most promising vaccines.

BUT, with your support, Unicef will deliver 2 billion Covid-19 vaccines for health workers and the most high risk people on our planet.

From buying and transporting supplies through to administering the vaccine, youâ€™ll help deliver history. Your donation will ensure:

  • vaccines get to even the most remote places in the world
  • vaccines are safely stored using cold chain equipment
  • health workers are protected and trained to vaccinate their communities

Donating whatever you can to â€˜twinâ€™ the vaccine you have, or will soon be receiving in the UK to another person in a poorer country will really help. A gift of Â£44 could transport 25 doses of Covid-19 vaccines.

Donating through JustGiving is simple, fast and totally secure. Your details are safe with JustGiving - they'll never sell them on or send unwanted emails. Once you donate, they'll send your money directly to the charity. So it's the most efficient way to donate - saving time and cutting costs for the charity.

Unicef ensures more children get life-saving food, vaccinations, education and protection than anyone else. With your help, we can build a safer world for children. unicef.org.uk
charity.name: Unicef UK
story: I am fundraising because Unicef urgently need funds to expand the scale and scope of their work supporting children affected by coronavirus, especially in countries with weaker health systems. Just Â£30 could provide a full kit to protect a health-worker on the frontline, including gloves, masks and coveralls, while just Â£43 could help provide 1,680 pairs of disposable gloves for health workers. The impact of a large-scale outbreak of coronavirus on children, especially poor and vulnerable children, has been immense. Children are at risk from the disease, but also from the disruption to health and education services, impacts on caregivers, and separation from family members. Unicef has been working closely with governments and the World Health Organization (WHO) since the start of the coronavirus outbreak. Donations made to my page will help to limit the spread of the virus and reduce the impact on children and families.

charity.description: Malaria No More UK mobilises governments, influencers, businesses and the public to end deaths from malaria and wipe out the disease for good. Our mission is to catalyse and inspire the global partnerships, leadership and financing to make malaria no more in a generation.
charity.name: MALARIA NO MORE UK
story: In 2019 it is estimated that 409,000 people around the world died from malaria - a preventable disease - the majority being children under five and pregnant women (source: WHO). 2021 is a vital year in the global campaign to make our world one without malaria. This coming June, the Commonwealth Heads of Government Meeting and the vitally important Kigali Summit on malaria and neglected tropical diseases will take place in Rwanda. The summit marks a historic moment that will unite global leaders and put a spotlight on the importance of renewed action in fighting malaria. We need more action, more innovation, more funding and more political leadership to defeat malaria and move forward stronger in this new global health landscape. Across Rentokil Initial, colleagues are taking part in a 9,000km Race to Kigali (the distance between our HQ and Kigali, Rwanda), including teams from America, Australia, Asia, Europe, the Middle East, Caribbean, Africa, HR, IT, Finance, M&A and Legal. By combining the efforts of colleagues walking, running or cycling, each team will â€˜reachâ€™ the distance to Kigali. This is our global effort to raise funds and show our support for this vital cause. It all starts on Monday 15 February through to the UNâ€™s World Malaria Day on 25 April. Andy Ransom: "As a proud patron of Malaria No More UK, I am asking my colleagues at Rentokil Initial, as well as friends, family and associates to get involved in the Race to Kigali. In doing so, helping raise incredibly important funding for Malaria No More UK at such a critical time. Rentokil Initial Cares, our charitable fund, will match every Â£1 raised up to Â£100,000.â€ Together we can achieve a Zero Malaria world within a generation. Please show your support.

charity.description: WaterAid is an international not-for-profit, determined to make clean water, decent toilets and good hygiene normal for everyone, everywhere within a generation. Only by tackling these three essentials in ways that last can people change their lives for good.
charity.name: WaterAid
eventName: Lands End to John O Groats
story:
I'm in my 84th year and have benefitted from help given by many excellent organisations, so my hope is to raise some money in support of a very deserving charity.

I have restricted vision, the result of several strokes. I also have reduced mobility caused by severe arthritis. I have had four knee replacements (so that's a total of six knees including the ones I was born with!). The most recent knee replacement was performed at Wrightington hospital, Wigan, where I had a unique procedure, and was told by the surgeon that this was the first such operation in Europe.

My plan is to cycle and walk the 1200 KM from Lands End to
John O Groats (cycling on my exercise bike and walking with walking aids around my home town of Lytham St Annes). I started this at the beginning of January and am keeping a careful log of my total distance each day.

It's going to take quite a few months, and I'll be posting my progress as I go, so please come back and have a look from time to time to see how I'm getting on.

Jeff.
title: Jeff's journey - Lands End to John O Groats

charity.name: WaterAid
story: I'm walking for water so others don't have to. I'm walking for the millions of women and children who walk distances every day to get the water they need for themselves and their families to survive. I'm walking to raise funds so we can make clean water normal for everyone, everywhere. Clean water is a human right that everyone, everywhere should enjoy. But around the world 1 in 10 people have no choice but to drink dirty water, often from remote sources, risking their health, their safety and their chances in life. With clean water, people have an equal chance to be healthy, educated and financially secure. Communities can thrive.

charity.description: WaterAid is an international not-for-profit, determined to make clean water, decent toilets and good hygiene normal for everyone, everywhere within a generation. Only by tackling these three essentials in ways that last can people change their lives for good.
charity.name: WaterAid
story: I'm walking for water so others don't have to. I'm walking for the millions of women and children who walk distances every day to get the water they need for themselves and their families to survive. I'm walking to raise funds so we can make clean water normal for everyone, everywhere. Clean water is a human right that everyone, everywhere should enjoy. But around the world 1 in 10 people have no choice but to drink dirty water, often from remote sources, risking their health, their safety and their chances in life. With clean water, people have an equal chance to be healthy, educated and financially secure. Communities can thrive.

charity.description: CARE International is one of the worldâ€™s leading aid agencies working in over 80 countries around the globe. We seek a world of hope, tolerance and social justice, with  women and girls at the centre, where poverty has been overcome, and people live with equal opportunities in security and dignity.
charity.name: CARE International UK
eventName: Pennyâ€™s 31000 March in aid of Yemen
story:
After five years of conflict, most of the population in Yemen needs humanitarian assistance. They have a lack of basic healthcare, severe food shortages and limited clean water.  

CARE is focused on helping the most vulnerable people, through distributing food to families in need, and cash vouchers so that families can purchase for themselves the food they need.

Over a year of fighting and fuel shortages has destroyed water pipes and water pumping facilities, so CARE is rehabilitating water sources and providing water tanks so women and children can get safe drinking water without having to travel long distances.

CARE is also providing hygiene kits, paying special attention to womens and children's needs.

Thank you for reading. For more information please visit the dedicated Yemen Crisis page on CARE's website: www.careinternational.org.uk/emergencies/yemen-crisis
